    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:8e4c3d04-5c89-41e0-8582-ec711bb73a8f",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 9-year-old girl who looks tired and mildly ill, sitting curled on the exam table with a small bucket nearby in case she vomits again. Her cheeks are slightly flushed, her lips a bit dry, and she clutches her lower abdomen between waves of cramping pain. She is alert and interactive but less energetic than usual, answering questions softly while glancing often to her mother for reassurance. She has had frequent loose stools since the previous evening, along with nausea, low-grade fever, and reduced appetite.\n\nAt baseline, {patientName} is an active elementary school student who enjoys playground games, drawing animals, and watching cartoons with her younger cousin after school. She lives with her mother, father, and older brother in a busy household where everyone usually eats dinner together. Over the weekend, the family attended a neighborhood picnic, and two days later she developed abdominal cramps and diarrhea after several children there were reported to have \"stomach flu.\" She has been drinking less than usual today and has only nibbled on crackers.\n\nHer mother says {patientName} is usually healthy, cheerful, and talkative, with no major chronic illnesses. Today she appears uncomfortable but not toxic, shifting position frequently because of crampy diffuse abdominal pain. She has no blood in the stool and no severe focal abdominal tenderness, but she does look mildly dehydrated, with decreased tears and dry mucous membranes.\n\nThe family is close-knit, and her parents are attentive and appropriately worried, especially because she has had six episodes of watery diarrhea and two episodes of non-bloody vomiting in the last 12 hours. Her brother recently had a brief self-limited diarrheal illness. At school, {patientName} is in the fourth grade and generally does well academically, though today she would much rather be home resting under a blanket with her favorite stuffed rabbit."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:5650847b-5452-47bb-bdf3-cf8102d147f1",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
